WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
[Amit Varma]: Given what cricket means for so many Indians, it's tempting to draw parallels between the

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:14.680
[Amit Varma]: story of cricket and the story of India. In some ways, cricket reflects how Indian society

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:19.000
[Amit Varma]: has changed over the last few decades. We started out uncertain of our place in the

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.120
[Amit Varma]: world, trying to find our feet, hobbled by an inferiority complex, looking for pride

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:29.680
[Amit Varma]: in small constellations, but eventually opening up to the world and asserting ourselves. But

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:34.360
[Amit Varma]: this comparison only goes so far. Our cricket has flourished to a point where India dominates

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:39.920
[Amit Varma]: this game, especially in a commercial sense. In some ways, it also embodies the best of

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:45.160
[Amit Varma]: what this country can be. It is inclusive of players from the remotest parts and showcases

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:50.560
[Amit Varma]: a healthy way to love your nation. I contrast that with the state of the nation today, where

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:55.760
[Amit Varma]: our economy is in a precarious place, our society is facing so many different kinds

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:01.920
[Amit Varma]: of ruptures, our politics has become so polarizing and toxic. George Orwell once spoke of sport

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:07.080
[Amit Varma]: as war minus the shooting. He was alluding to the ugly tribal instincts that sport can

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:12.280
[Amit Varma]: bring out. But cricket, it seems to me, has evolved to a place where it can sometimes

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:17.160
[Amit Varma]: take us beyond that tribal place. If that's so, then that's one more thing to love about

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:35.600
[Unknown]: Indian cricket. And there's a lot to love about it.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:40.160
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Ayaz Memon, cricket journalist for

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:45.080
[Amit Varma]: 42 years now, and indeed such a legend of cricket journalism that his Twitter handle

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:51.400
[Amit Varma]: at Cricketwala is basically how he is known. Ayaz is the editor of a superb new anthology

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:56.540
[Amit Varma]: called Indian Innings, the journey of Indian cricket since 1947. The book has selections

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:02.120
[Amit Varma]: from over 60 writers spanning the decades since independence and captures many of the

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:07.280
[Amit Varma]: fine milestones and characters of the game. In some ways, it's not just about the journey

00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:11.760
[Amit Varma]: of cricket, but also the journey of cricket writing. I'm honored to have a couple of pieces

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:17.920
[Amit Varma]: in this anthology, and the rest of the writers constitute a who's who of Indian cricket writing.

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:22.040
[Amit Varma]: It's a fabulous book to sit back with and get a sense of the rich history of this fine

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:27.720
[Amit Varma]: game, which, as Ashish Nandy once said, is quote, an Indian game invented by the English,

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:32.560
